"The Sea is Ours": Bolivia, which has no outlet to the sea, hopes the court will grant it an outlet to the Pacific Ocean
The Marines are patrolling the busy shipping yard at La Paz.
The flag of the ocean is reported on public buildings.
The maritime bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are crying out: "We have the right to the sea.
It's our duty to return it.
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost seacoast to Chile during the 19th-century resource wars is still alive  as is the longing to sail the Pacific again.
As Bolivia awaits the International Court of Justice's verdict expected on October 1 after five years of proceedings, these hopes may be at their highest level in decades.
"Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and peace and, of course, is optimistic about the outcome", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
The crowds of Bolivians across the country will be watching the International Court of Justice's ruling on big screens and hoping that the court in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia's position that Chile, after decades of arduous negotiations, is obliged to negotiate the ceding of a sovereign access to the sea to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president who faces a controversial battle to be re-elected next year, may also benefit from Monday's ruling.
"We're hoping to bring back the Pacific Ocean", he promised by the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in Bolivia's favor and that little would change if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and has stated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the International Court of Justice's ruling comes just six months after the final hearings means the case was "not complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Instead of promoting Bolivia's interests, the last four years may have set them back.
"The issue of access to the sea is currently the focus of the Bolivian leadership", said Zárate.
Morales' bellicose rhetoric has buried all goodwill in Chile, he believes.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue the dialogue, but after this it will be extremely difficult to negotiate.
These two countries haven't exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, disagreed with the statement that the court made the decision unusually quickly.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an unprecedented opportunity to begin a new era in relations with Chile" and an opportunity "to end 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales  still one of the most favored presidents in Latin America  used the maritime issue as a political stick.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean", he added.
