John Edward: The language skills that citizens of the world need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, and is further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the careers they want to pursue and to become citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement the aforementioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be the favourite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it goes to his heart.
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results from this year's final exams show that the highest grades in languages were achieved by the students of the independent schools.
In total, 68% of the students who studied foreign languages received excellent marks.
Data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils received an excellent grade in Mandarin, while 72% of pupils learning German, 69% of pupils learning French and 63% of pupils learning Spanish also received the highest possible grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as electives are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of a workforce with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming imperative to prepare young people for careers.
With the increasing demand for language skills in jobs, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career choice, those who have learned to speak a foreign language will feel the benefits of such a long-term skill in the future.
A person who speaks more than one language can communicate directly with foreigners, and this gives him an advantage over his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the United Kingdom do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of respondents, or 15%.
So investing in language learning is very important for kids today.
If children learn more languages, especially those spoken in developing economies, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers different languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will opt for languages that are considered to be the most important in the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scotland's independent schools provide an environment for children to learn, prepare and equip themselves with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
There is no denying that in today's global business environment, language skills are so important to the future of every country that they must be reflected in education.
So, knowing modern languages really should be seen as an 'international communication skill'.
Independent schools will continue to offer choice of language, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It's got to be done right.
John Edward is the headmaster of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
