North Korea has announced that there is no chance for unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions are increasing mistrust of the United States and that there is no chance that North Korea will unilaterally disarm and give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea took "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and deciding to stop the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
"However, we have not received a satisfactory response from the United States of America", he added.
"If we don't have faith in the United States, we don't have faith in our national security, and there's no way we're going to be the first to disarm unilaterally under these circumstances".
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization that would see sanctions on North Korea gradually lifted, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to the joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever meeting between the current US president and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim gave a promise to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the U.S. has made it a condition that Pyongyang give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also ignored calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The US insists on denuclearisation first and is increasing pressure through sanctions to force its way to its goal, even opposing the declaration of an end to the war, Ri added.
The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that continuing sanctions increases mistrust.
Ri did not mention whether there were any plans for a second Kim-Trump meeting that the US president had talked about earlier in the week at the United Nations.
But the minister pointed out that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in have held as many as three meetings in the last five months and added: "If South Korea, not the US, had sought denuclearisation, the denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill".
Regardless, Secretary Ri's tone of speech was vastly different from last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and declared that a missile strike on the continental United States was inevitable after evil President Trump called Kim a "human missile" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, this year at the United Nations praised Kim for his courage in disarmament, but added that there was still much work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearises.
Trump said on Wednesday that there is no time frame for denuclearization and added: "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia have expressed the view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must strictly continue until complete, final and verified denuclearization is achieved".
The Security Council unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Riyadh at the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second meeting.
