North Korea has arranged a meeting with Moon this month to discuss the dismantling of the missile site and nuclear complex that will take place if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He added that Kim had revealed to him that these "appropriate measures" relate to the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and certain steps towards stabilizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course on how to get good rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat the increasingly prevalent culture of caffeinated learning and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world's best universities often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed what he believes is the first course of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea for the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
And at the end of the lecture, this girl came up to me and said, "Why did I only find out about this in my senior year of college?"
She said that no one had told her how important sleep was, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The first class this year will teach students how good sleep habits help with academic and athletic performance and overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, says that the university decided to introduce the course after students were observed to have a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks involves a picture of a student's dorm room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how lack of sleep affects performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
During the class, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus is displayed with interactive icons that encourage students to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that student behavior won't change overnight.
But we feel that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect your health", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in studying all night before exams still exists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students prove that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Sleep also helps to combat obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, putting it in a state of starvation and causing constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his classes at Harvard freshman year.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to expand the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, it plans to ask all graduates to complete a similar course of study before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on the alarm both at bedtime and at waking hours, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted from electronic display screens, as well as LED lights that can disrupt circadian rhythms and cause sleep problems.
