An experimental vaccine is showing promising results in patients with various types of cancer.
In one woman who was treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize bad cells, ovarian cancer was in remission for more than 18 months.
The procedure involves taking immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory to ' identify' a protein called HER2 that is common to many types of cancer, and then injecting the cells again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results show that we have a very promising vaccine".
